Color is the children from the marriage between light and darkness. Each of those children represents different stages in life. 

Red is the 1st color & youngest child. It represents the begging of life and is the symbol of birth. It’s lighting @sashamukh ‘s legs & her pointe shoes which are holding her up with strength & embody where her journey first began, her childhood dream of being a ballerina. It’s her one direct point of contact with the dance floor, providing a solid foundation and where her beginning meets the present.

 Green connects the purity & joy of our youth with the knowledge & wisdom of our life experience. It’s the only color in the middle of the spectrum reflecting on the stages of the beginning & end. It’s the color of the soul and represents knowledge. It’s on the base of this image & the color that most represents Sasha (at this moment in her life). She earned and reached the highest rank but felt there was still room to grow. This required her to step back and reflect. The opportunity to grow placed her back in the middle (rank). She’s in a stage where she’s been before but revisiting it with added knowledge and experience. Green isolates materiality from the destiny of spirituality & it’s what she embodied in pursuing growth. 

Orange is gracefully descending from above. It provides warmth & represents the need & relationship with family. Here it also represents Sasha’s parents who were both former dancers & introduced her to ballet. The orange transitioning to green symbolizes the inspiration passed down from one generation to the next. The green is directly connected & touching Sasha through her pointe shoe that leads us directly the final color.

 Blue, which represents freedom & liberty. It’s the only color directly falling on Sasha & over her heart. Blue is conductive to keen intelligence but more importantly it’s the color of thought & intuition. Being guided by your intuition is what’s most important to being an artist and creating work that’s sincere. Sasha following her heart is what brought her to where she’s at today. 

Thank you for sharing your story with me. Be sure to go see Sasha perform at @sfballet if you’re in town.

Arrival 📸 @lapetitefrench_ 

It’s interesting how things workout. Mathilde and I worked together relentlessly before she left for France. We got a lot work done that I’m extremely proud of and not long ago we were complete strangers.

We crossed paths and met because I was meeting with the amazing @pemberley_ann in the lobby at the ballet and Mathilde happened to pass by, saw me and we (briefly) met. I connected with Pemberly because I had such a great experience working with @nicole.moyer_ 

I mentioned how great it was working with Nicole to someone who’s input I value and they said I needed to meet/work with Pemberly and they introduced us. In short, bc of Nicole, I met Pemberly. Bc of Pemberly I met Mathilde. 

The reason all of the above happened and why I’ve continued to photograph ballet is because for 4yrs+ I’ve had the privilege to work with @sashadesola who consistently performs at an extremely high level and always leaves me feeling inspired and excited to continue creating. She set her own mark and brought me up to her level. 

I was never supposed to meet Sasha. Meeting her was truly a blessing. She’s the ballerina who I’ve photographed the most and has been invaluable in me growing as an artist and developing my creative process 🙏🏼

I’m so thankful for everything that happened or didn’t workout because I ended up being  blessed crossing paths with amazing people despite all of my shortcomings.

As I look at the recent work I just completed it’s interesting to realize how things can come together. 

I’m extremely grateful for everyone I’ve met and worked with. Thank you for the opportunity to collaborate and create with you 🙏🏼

Lacing up pointe shoes with @nicole.moyer_ 🎥🎬 check out that push in flare. I love cinematography. It opens so many possibilities. Behind the scenes photo and clip at the end. 

Everything was lit using 2 @hobolite Avant with the fresnal lens and a mini boomed overhead to flare the lens. The warm/cool tone was done by using the bi-color feature on the lights 🙌🏼

Filmed using the @fujifilmx_us #GFX100s and taking advantage of the bigger sensor to get vista vision aspect ratio. 

Graded in Davinci resolve using @dehancer.film

During our first photo shoot, I was in conversation with @nicole.moyer_ , Corps de Ballet member at @sfballet  I asked her what she’s aiming to do every time she performs. She responded by saying:

“My ultimate goal is to show the beauty [in] God's creation. I believe we're created in his image and are supposed to be like him. In the most ideal version of ourselves, we are like him. We can strive for perfection, but we can never be there. We ultimately portray everything that God can do. And so when I dance, I want to show God's beauty, his creation, everything that he's made us to be able to do, complex and simple, and big and small. Ultimately point the glory back to God.”

When I heard her response, I thought it was extremely beautiful and I wanted to create a portrait/image of her that reflected what she said. Time was not on my side as our session was during the middle of her season, and we were scheduled to shoot late from only 7-10pm (including setup/breakdown time). To make things worse, I wasn’t sure if I could create the image I had in mind as I hadn’t done something like this before. I would need to figure it out on the spot which is usually not a good idea specially when pressed for time. 

10pm came at the blink of an eye but Nicole and I kept working. We actually kept going to almost midnight. 

Because of Nicole’s dedication to keep working with me I had sufficient time to create this image as a direct inspiration and impression to what she said. Thank you Nicole for your time and sharing your story with me. I know how precious your time off is during the season and I appreciate you greatly for working with me.

In her own words. @nicole.moyer_ Corps de Ballet member at @sfballet Nicole thank you for kindness, compassion and patience with me. It’s an absolute blessing working with you. 
.

I asked @nicole.moyer_ what it feels like going on stage, right before the curtains go up. She responded:

“Right before the curtain comes up when the lights are beginning to come on, it's this moment of peace and solidarity, and just being completely in yourself. Just a next level of focus, but also a greater you waiting to come out. We become more than ourselves when we're on stage, and in that moment is where we get amplified, and we become something much bigger than we are.”

That was such a beautiful and poetic response. I wanted to visually show peace, solidarity, being completely in yourself and a next level of focus. Which seems like a daunting task. However, Nicole’s words lead the way. I decided the best way to show all of the above was to not just throw everything out of focus, but skew the perspective/focus inward towards her. 

To accomplish this, I removed the front lens element and reversed it on the Mir 1B 37mm lens and photographed her wide open. To show a next level of focus, I threw everything out of focus except her and skewed the environment towards her.

To show “in that moment is where we get amplified, and we become something much bigger than we are”, I used lighting and color to complete the look and feel of she described. Nicole, thank you for the inspiration. 

On a lighting technical note, since this was the same day we were filming, I continued using the @hobolite lights and took advantage of the bi-color feature. Swipe right for a behind the scenes.

Thank you PPSCV for having me and everyone who came to my talk last night 🙏🏼 I’m always grateful for the opportunity to share my work and process with others. Specially in person and letting people see the work in a tangible form. Thank you @bayphotolab for making my work look amazing 🙏🏼 and @sjcamerastore for hosting.

Meet Enyel Cruz. He told me an important life lesson he’s learned [at just 11 years old] is that you need to value what you have. When he lived in Nicaragua, he was able to sleep well in his own bed. Here his back hurts as he has to sleep on the floor at the corner of the basketball gym at Buena Vista Horace Mann K-8 Community School in San Francisco. 

Enyel and his family are seeking asylum do to the human rights violations in Nicaragua which include extrajudicial executions, arbitrary detentions, torture, arbitrary deprivation of nationality and of the right to remain in one's own country. The current government has persecuted, criminalized, and eliminated any opposing voices. Creating a situation where people are forced to leave everything they have, flee Nicaragua and seek a new beginning by any means possible. 

Buena Vista Horace Mann K-8 Community School in San Francisco, opens its doors to families in needs and gives them a place to sleep at night. They have to be up at 6am and ready to clear everything to make way for the school day. While Enyel and his sister Ashley go to school, his parents look for any work they can find while they wait on progress on their asylum case.

Portrait of Enyel Cruz and his sister Ashley Arguello Cruz taken at Burna Vista Horace Mann K-8 community school. The school provides them and their family a place to sleep as they seek asylum in US from Nicaragua. 

While the school provides families a place to sleep and something to eat, Ashley usually skips dinner as they don’t have an option for their meal will be. Her dream is to become an actor.

Photographed for the San Francisco Standard.

Portrait of 6 year old Alexa Mendoza taken at Buena Vista Horace Mann K-8 Community School in San Francisco, where her and family spend the night. She has two older brothers ages 15 and 22. Her father, Jose Mendoza left everything he had in Nicaragua to move his entire family to the US for a new start. 

The reason they have to live/sleep in a shelter, is because when seeking alyssum one can’t legally start working right away which makes it difficult to provide for your family. Although he’s educated and fully qualified to work he can’t be employed. When asked what he thought of the situation he’s facing, Jose replied saying that all new beginnings are hard but you have to make an effort. You have to want it. 

The dictatorship in Nicaragua goes to schools and pays student’s to rally and support them and protest against any opposition. If students refuse to cooperate they can be arrested or face dire consequences. Those are just some of the human rights violations taking place that made him leave and move his family here. 

Jose said that his daughter doesn’t fully understand what’s going on and that she think’s moving and everything they’re going through is just a game. While she may not fully understand everything right now, she will later on. From first hand experience, I can tell you she’s fully aware of what’s happening. I was her same exact age when I had leave Nicaragua with my mom and older brother. I remember the day we left. Seeing how focused and concerned my mother was. My father had to leave a year earlier to seek political asylum here and it took a year to bring us to the US to be reunited. 

There’s no elegant way for me to express this as it’s frustrating seeing history repeat itself and knowing that the same motherfucker that tore my family apart & made my dad & mom go through hell, is still doing the same exact thing to innocent people today. 

I was working directly w/ the writer as the translator for this assignment. It’s certainly a unique situation when you already know the answers to the questions & also experienced the same circumstances too. Both of the families from this assignment happened to be from Nicaragua, it wasn’t planned.

Feeling extremely grateful 🙏🏼 So blessed to start a new decade of life this Friday. It’s been such a gift working with amazing ballerinas the passed 5 years. 

Recently with @lapetitefrench_  We worked for 5-6 weeks straight. I was able to shoot everything I’ve ever wanted in that short timeframe. She’s actually now the ballerina I’ve done the most session’s with!!!

I learned so much and pushed myself creatively. Mathilde is a collaborator/muse you dream about having. Being around her dedication, passion and kindness left me a better person. 

The time we worked together flew by. If I didn’t have photos/work we did as visual evidence, I would think I hallucinated everything, ha! 

Excited to find a way to properly share all the work we did. I have so much to look forward to and busy week ahead 🙏🏼

I’ve been fortunate enough to work with some elite athletes over the years. On two occasions, one of those athletes was Lebron James. Something he said that left an impression on me was:

“what’s known doesn’t need to be said”

That concept may seem very simple on the surface but very few can execute it. Those who can are able to demand excellence simply with their presence. Are able to bring out the best in you without saying a word. 

I’ve been working with ballet dancers for five years. Out of those five years, four of them have been with @sashadesola She embodies that quote and those qualities to the fullest extent. She consistently performs at an extremely high level. She’s immensely talented, accomplished and has supreme confidence but never comes near arrogance. That’s elegance and grace in its purest form.

As a person, she naturally rises above and stands out with her kindness and charisma. Those qualities are truly admirable and rare but she makes it seem effortlessly. 

When you’re the photographer it’s your responsibility to make the talent feel safe and comfortable during the session. Whenever I work with Sasha, it’s the other way around. She makes me feel safe and comfortable creatively, which allows me to push myself to failure without caution. Elevating me as artists, and ultimately leading to me becoming a better person. 

For four years I’ve had the privilege of Sasha consistently uplifting me. I’ve also met a lot amazing people because of her. I can’t speak about working with ballet dancer without mentioning her name. Amazing people and greatness needs to be acknowledged. Sasha I appreciate you more than words can express. Being able to work and collaborate with you has been a blessing. Thank you 🙏🏼

In researching dance, I learned that statically speaking. Aspiring dancers have a 3% chance of turning professional. Out of every 1,000 souls that dedicated their childhoods to fulfill their dreams, 970 won’t succeed. 

When it comes to ballet, even less get promoted to a higher rank. And only a selected few defy the odds and become prima ballerinas. 

I’m generally obsessed with people who are obsessed about excelling in something. Which generally leads me to working with athletes. 

Having the opportunity to work with people who excel at what they do , you tend to notice certain qualities and characteristics that they have. What I find fascinating is that both Sasha and Mathilde possess those qualities, are principle ballerinas but I have a completely different way of working with them. 

I would say they’re almost opposites, and the approach to collaborate and work with them is extremely contrasting. Logically speaking one would think that I would prefer a single approach or that I wouldn’t be able to work with two different styles. But I’m deeply intrigued that despite the collaboration process being so different, everything still falls into place. 

Sasha and Mathilde are the two ballerinas I’ve worked with the most. What they both have in common is an extraordinary desire and passion for what they do. And both are extremely caring, thoughtful, compassionate, creative, smart and have hearts made of gold. 

I’m extremely grateful and fortunate to have been able to work both you 🙏🏼 

Speaking of statistics, this one perhaps is the most important one. Out of the entire world’s population, only 2% have eyes as devastating beautiful as mine. Combined that 2% statics with both of them defying the odds and becoming elite ballerinas and you’re basically witnessing a miracle when you see our work 😂😂😂

I’m ending it on that note because tomorrow is my birthday and I’m Leo 🦁 😂🙃

Blessed to see another year 🙏🏼thank you everyone for the birthday wishes. I’m so grateful and happy for the knowledge and experience that comes with time. It’s truly a gift. 

While it’s my birthday, I’ve always celebrated my mom. She’s the one who gave me life today. She’s the one who had sleepless nights taking care of me for the following years in the harshest conditions during civil war in Nicaragua. Giving her roses is the least I can do considering everything she’s given me and sacrificed for me. 

I was also blessed with an amazing father who at 29 years old, had to leave my mom alone with me and older brother (we were 4 & 6 at the time) to seek political asylum here in the US. As an adult, I can’t even comprehend how stressful and difficult that must have been for both of them. 

Every opportunity I’ve had is a product of the love and sacrifice they made. I’m truly blessed 🙏🏼

Today is #nationalballetday and I want to give a huge shout-out to three extraordinary prima ballerinas I've had the honor to work with. They are also the three dancers I've photographed the most!

The first principal ballerina I had the privilege of working with was the amazing @christineshevchenko Working with her was a career-changing experience and the reason I began focusing on ballet. It was the first time I ever collaborated with someone at the top of their profession who was equally dedicated to creating the best possible work as I am. We worked on our project over Easter weekend for three days, and on the first day, we shot for 12 hours! Her dedication and pursuit of excellence in her craft and art left a lasting impression on me.

The ballerina with whom I've had the longest working relationship is @sashadesola  She has set a standard well above and beyond anything I've ever seen or experienced, consistently performing at the highest level as an artist and ballerina, while also having the purest and kindest heart. No photograph I take can capture her elegance, strength, and tenacity. Her presence alone demands excellence. Working with her is a direct blessing from God. You've made me a better person.

The ballerina with whom I've had the honor to work the most is @lapetitefrench_ Mathilde, I'm still not sure if you're a real person or someone I just imagined. In barely six weeks, we accomplished more than I have in the past five years with any other ballerina. Your kindness and compassion are angelic, and your dedication to ballet and your son is relentless, unbreakable, and awe-inspiring. You pushed me creatively. In the 18 years I've been a photographer, I've never met someone as thoughtful and compassionate as you. You have a heart of gold. 

I'm extremely grateful and feel blessed to have had the opportunity to work with each of you. I can't thank you enough. Thank you for being you. 🙏🏼
las flores crecen hacia el sol 📸 @lapetitefrench_

During our first session, I asked @alexisfranci_ about his preparation on performance days and if he does anything before going on stage to get ready. He shared his process with me which was extremely inspiring and said the following:

“Before I go out I always say a phrase to myself. This is the first time I'll be sharing it to someone, actually. I always say: 

‘I was born to do this.’

And then I go. Whatever I'm doing, even if it’s just like standing there or even if I'm doing one of the hardest Pas de deux or if I'm doing a variation, anything. Always, before I go, I say:
  ‘I was born to do this’
and then I go. Basically nothing goes through my mind. Except, the last minute, I do choreography really fast. Just to make sure like it's there. And then I do that phrase and then I go.”

I wanted to create an image of him that embodied that spirit. I used the color red, because in the philosophy that colors are the children of light, red is the first child. It’s the color of blood, the symbol of birth. And the meaning of that color aligns perfectly with Alexis’ phrase. 

After working together to figure out the posing, lighting and composition, this is the image we created. I can’t thank you enough Alexis for sharing your story and process with me and giving me an opportunity to create work that’s sincere that left me inspired.

Excited to release the short film I made with @lapetitefrench_ during her final weeks in San Francisco later this week. There’s so much we have that didn’t make the cut and I’m grateful to be able to share it. 

Here Mathilde talks about her first time in the dressing room and what the room means to her.

@lapetitefrench_ was at San Francisco Ballet for ten years. We crossed paths 8 weeks before she left and moved back to France. We worked together relentlessly for 6 weeks. I was able to photograph and film her final weeks in San Francisco. 

I’m grateful to be releasing the short film we made tomorrow. I’ll be posting it on my YouTube channel. Excited to spread the heartfelt knowledge and insight Mathilde shared with me. I’m so thankful for this opportunity that was a complete blessing 🙏🏼 

Her work ethic, kindness and compassion are at levels I’ve never witnessed before. We stood up until 2am to complete one of the interviews. In between dropping off her son at daycare, rehearsals, personal training, gyrotonic, strength and conditioning and being a single parent she still found the time to shoot portraits and film! Thank you for all the inspiration Mathilde. 

I’m making a behind the scenes video of the work we did. From a technical standpoint, I filmed her using the GFX100s for the Vista Vison aspect ratio. If there’s anything specific you’d like me cover, comment below. Excited for tomorrow 🙌🏼🎥🎬
